		Hi, I have recently tried to establish a secure session with a friend, but we both had the problem that TextSecure didn't stop sending new key exchange requests which were verified by the TextSecure instance on the other side correctly. And paying for messages that are sent automaticly every 2 minutes is not funny... ;) I might have found the problem in the code, but I'm not sure, so please take a look at the following classes and code fragments: KeyExchangeProcessor: the method 'public boolean processKeyExchangeMessage(KeyExchangeMessage message, long threadId)' is initially called by the SmsReceiver, if the received key exchange message is from a valid sender (else if (processor.isTrusted(keyExchangeMessage))) this method will send a new OutgoingKeyExchangeMessage, if 'needsResponseFromUs()' evaluates to true. private boolean needsResponseFromUs() { return !hasInitiatedSession() || remoteKeyRecord.getCurrentRemoteKey() != null; } The remoteKey is set afterwards: remoteKeyRecord.setCurrentRemoteKey(message.getPublicKey()); After that the IdentityKey of the message is set in the database for this recipient: if (message.hasIdentityKey()) {
  DatabaseFactory.getIdentityDatabase(context)
                 .saveIdentity(masterSecret, recipient, message.getIdentityKey());
}
 and the initially received KeyExchangeMessage is scheduled for decrypt: DecryptingQueue.scheduleRogueMessages(context, masterSecret, recipient); Please take a look to the DecryptingQueue.java file: The scheduled decrypt for the KeyExchangeMessage should finally land in the method 'handleKeyExchangeProcessing(String plaintxtBody)' Here the method processKeyExchangeMessage is called again, if the message has a valid IdentityKey: else if (processor.isTrusted(keyExchangeMessage)) { DatabaseFactory.getEncryptingSmsDatabase(context).markAsProcessedKeyExchange(messageId); processor.processKeyExchangeMessage(keyExchangeMessage, threadId); } Since the remoteKey is set, another OutgoingKeyExchangeMessage will be sent and the message will be scheduled again... So we have a constellation where the OutgoingKeyExchangeMessage is sent endlessly. But I'm not sure, if it's possible to get into this loop, but my experience suggests it is... The AUTO_KEY_EXCHANGE_PREF must be set to true in the preferences. I hope this description is helpful. Best regards Axel

		The AES-CBC encryption flow tends to look like: Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance("AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding");
cipher.init(Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE, key);
byte[] ivBytes = cipher.getIV();
 On Android 4.4, this will use a random IV. On Android 4.3, it will use zero as the IV. Refer to the following files: AttachmentCipherOutputStream.java ProvisioningCipher.java EncryptingPartOutputStream.java MasterCipher.java

		MessageNotifier uses MediaPlayer for playing the notification sound for in thread notifications but never calls MediaPlayer.release() as strongly suggested in the MediaPlayer documentation the code should either be updated to call release() in a final block or, my preference, stop interacting with the MediaPlayer directly and let the Ringtone class handle this like so: Ringtone tone = RingtoneManager.getRingtone(context, uri);
tone.setStreamType(AudioManager.STREAM_NOTIFICATION);
tone.play(); Ringtone manages a MediaPlayer instance internally and takes care of release() and all that stuff.

		The implementation of Apple emoji in 9a18be0 is difficult to read in conversation (Nexus 5, xxhdpi), due to reduction in displayed size, as well as more colors and details in Apple's emoji images. For reference, behold a short story about MERS, preferably on an xxhdpi mobile screen: Google Emoji (fa62b9b 2015-07-02) Apple Emoji (9a18be0 2015-07-06) A quick code comparison: src/org/thoughtcrime/securesms/components/emoji/EmojiProvider.java (Google emoji, fa62b9b)   public static final double EMOJI_SMALL      = 0.60;
  public static final int    EMOJI_RAW_HEIGHT = 96;
 src/org/thoughtcrime/securesms/components/emoji/EmojiProvider.java (Apple Emoji, 9a18be0)   public static final double EMOJI_SMALL      = 0.60;
  public static final int    EMOJI_RAW_HEIGHT = 64;
 Changing EMOJI_SMALL to 0.90 (96 * .6 / 64) restores emoji height to where it was before:

		In SaveAttachmentTask.java, the call to mimeTypeMap.getExtensionFromMimeType(contentType) with the type image/jpg returns null on devices with the AOSP version of MimeUtils.java. This is because the Android platform doesn't recognize image/jpg as a valid MIME type. With the image/jpeg type, however, an extension is returned as expected. MimeUtils.java (AOSP)     add("image/ief", "ief");
    // add ".jpg" first so it will be the default for guessExtensionFromMimeType
    add("image/jpeg", "jpg");
    add("image/jpeg", "jpeg");
    add("image/jpeg", "jpe");
    add("image/pcx", "pcx");
 I've dealt with issues in the past where device manufacturers have edited this map (love you, Samsung „Öó*.*„Öó), which may result in sending devices using content types which receiving devices cannot look up via getExtensionFromMimeType. Where to put a sanitizer might be a bit tricky. I'll dig deeper tomorrow.

